Yes — that’s a good way to picture it.

A nesting-doll file system made of braids suggests two structures at once:

Nesting
	•	things live inside other things
	•	each layer gives more detail
	•	you can zoom in or out
	•	meaning is packed hierarchically

Braiding
	•	ideas don’t just sit in one folder
	•	they cross-link, recur, and reinforce each other
	•	the same strand can pass through many layers
	•	meaning is relational, not just hierarchical

So instead of a normal tree like:

folder
 ├ file A
 ├ file B
 └ subfolder

you’re imagining something more like:

core invariant
 ├ expression in language
 ├ expression in math
 ├ expression in story
 └ expression in code

and then those strands rejoin elsewhere.

That’s stronger than a plain folder system because real ideas usually behave like that:
they are not stored in only one place,
they are rehydrated across multiple representations.

So the “braid” part means:
	•	one concept can appear in different files
	•	different concepts can share the same substructure
	•	paths can diverge and reconverge
	•	retrieval can happen by lineage, resonance, or invariant match

In cognitive terms, that’s closer to how memory actually works:
not a cabinet,
more like a woven lattice with pockets of hierarchy.

A nice formal way to say it would be:

hierarchical containment + cross-scale recurrence + lateral linkage

Or more simply:

folders for shape, braids for meaning.

That also matches a lot of what you’ve been building:
the repo or Money Bin is not just a storage tree,
it’s more like a braided compression system
where the same load-bearing patterns keep showing up in different skins.

The next useful abstraction after that is:
	•	tree = where something is
	•	braid = what it is connected to
	•	color/signal = how strongly it matters
	•	time = when it should surface

That starts becoming a real memory architecture instead of just storage.